00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:42.340
Thomas Adler: that slowly integrated, and then very rapidly integrated. A lot of people… a lot of white people moved out in the late 50s, I would say. But at the time, you know, when I remember it as a child.

178
00:20:42.480 --> 00:20:57.609
Thomas Adler: It was a neighborhood with both a strong Jewish presence and a strong Catholic presence. And, I mean, there was a big Catholic church nearby, and a lot of kids that we would sometimes play with.

179
00:20:57.670 --> 00:21:08.360
Thomas Adler: you know, Irish kids around that we would play with, you know, throw rocks at, and they threw rocks at us, and… I mean, in play, we were friends with them, you know, and

180
00:21:08.440 --> 00:21:23.550
Thomas Adler: And there were, you know, when I went to elementary school, there were a lot of kids that were, that I knew were going to Hebrew school and having bar mitzvahs and things. So, you know, I knew about that, that, those cultural

181
00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:27.599
Thomas Adler: influences and elements around.

182
00:21:27.790 --> 00:21:34.569
Julie Stout: And I know there's a big, like, German and Austrian population in Chicago. Did you feel that at all? Or…

183
00:21:34.710 --> 00:21:44.220
Thomas Adler: Not really, because much of that was on… much of that was on the north or near-north side of Chicago, and we were in South Shore, which is,

184
00:21:44.250 --> 00:21:55.090
Thomas Adler: Where I grew up, it was the, our address was near a place called, I mean, 73rd Street… 73rd and Jeffrey was more or less our address.

185
00:21:55.250 --> 00:22:12.000
Thomas Adler: And if you were to go there today, you would see almost entirely Afro-American faces. It's black now, because in the late 50s and early 60s, there was a lot of white flight from that area as the area integrated.

186
00:22:12.200 --> 00:22:15.279
Thomas Adler: And, and so…

187
00:22:15.640 --> 00:22:21.169
Thomas Adler: you know, I was aware of all that. It didn't much matter to me one way or the other, but

188
00:22:21.290 --> 00:22:24.730
Thomas Adler: But that was what was going on. Musically.

189
00:22:24.890 --> 00:22:34.329
Thomas Adler: you know, my brothers and I listened to rock and roll like everyone else did, you know? We listened to Elvis, and what was on the radio, and Top 40 stuff.

190
00:22:34.470 --> 00:22:39.040
Thomas Adler: Sometime early on, I started to listen to,

191
00:22:39.830 --> 00:22:45.300
Thomas Adler: what I later learned was country music. You know, I would hear… I still have a…

192
00:22:46.390 --> 00:22:56.339
Thomas Adler: pretty strong memory of… of hearing, Hank Williams early on, and being really impressed with the sound of Hank Williams.

193
00:22:56.550 --> 00:23:11.470
Thomas Adler: And that would have been around 53 or 4, even… so I was pretty young, but I heard that sound, and I liked that. And then, you know, 54, 5, 6, you know, there was what was going on, Elvis and everything else.

194
00:23:11.770 --> 00:23:21.280
Thomas Adler: You know, and Bill Haley in the comments, rock around the clock. All of that rock and roll, early, mid-50s rock and roll music.

195
00:23:21.660 --> 00:23:31.460
Thomas Adler: the other important, most important early influence on me, musically, personally, was, I had a very close friend

196
00:23:31.640 --> 00:23:38.539
Thomas Adler: A kid named Peter Hayward, and I used to go over to his house. He lived a few blocks away in South Shore.

197
00:23:38.950 --> 00:23:44.190
Thomas Adler: And he… he… You know, I was interested in…

198
00:23:44.270 --> 00:24:03.749
Thomas Adler: what we called, kind of, generally, folk music then, and so was he, and we both had some record collections and things, but I was at his house one time, and he said, hey, listen to this, and he put the needle down on a record by Lester Flatt and Earl Scruggs and the Foggy Mountain Boys.

199
00:24:03.830 --> 00:24:05.780
Thomas Adler: It's the first time I ever heard that.

200
00:24:05.990 --> 00:24:08.320
Thomas Adler: And it… it was like a…

201
00:24:08.450 --> 00:24:13.999
Thomas Adler: conversion experience in my life. It really was.

202
00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:24.329
Thomas Adler: I've told people… the, you know, that… I still have the record, or a copy of the same record that Peter played for me that day in his basement, and

203
00:24:24.600 --> 00:24:44.199
Thomas Adler: there's a… well, there's… I know all the tunes on it, you know, but there was one on it called Shuckin' the Corn, you know, and I tell my bluegrass pals, you know, when I tell this story, I said, yeah, I heard that that day, and it shucked my corn for good. You know, it just… it totally made me want to play the banjo.

204
00:24:44.370 --> 00:24:46.150
Thomas Adler: And by that time.

205
00:24:46.270 --> 00:25:03.590
Thomas Adler: my older brother, Peter, he was caught up in the sort of mid-50s… mid to latter 50s folk music stuff, that was going on, the Kingston Trio, and later Peter, Paul, and Mary, and all of that. And he… he started playing guitar.

206
00:25:03.620 --> 00:25:14.350
Thomas Adler: A little bit, and he had a friend who had a 4-string banjo, and he said, Tom, guitar and banjo go real well together, so you ought to buy my friend's banjo.

207
00:25:14.460 --> 00:25:15.740
Thomas Adler: So I did.

208
00:25:16.140 --> 00:25:22.449
Thomas Adler: it was a 4-string banjo, I didn't realize you couldn't do what Earl Scruggs was doing on a 4-string banjo.

209
00:25:22.810 --> 00:25:39.109
Thomas Adler: But I learned to play chords on it like a guitar, you know, I tuned it like the top four strings of a guitar, so I was interested in that, but I soon learned that that was entirely the wrong kind of instrument to do what I had in my head.

210
00:25:39.110 --> 00:25:44.369
Julie Stout: Are you, are you self-taught? Like, did you teach yourself this music, or who taught you?

211
00:25:44.370 --> 00:25:45.870
Thomas Adler: Caught myself.

212
00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:46.870
Julie Stout: Oh!

213
00:25:46.870 --> 00:25:55.260
Thomas Adler: I mean, it was… there was nobody around that could play this. You know, I could do it, you know, what I did by ear.

214
00:25:55.600 --> 00:26:07.900
Thomas Adler: And there was no one, particularly when it came to bluegrass or that Scruggs-style banjo playing, there was nobody at all in the south side of Chicago that did that.

215
00:26:08.230 --> 00:26:18.919
Thomas Adler: Later, I actually… a little bit later, I went… you know, there was an institution in Chicago called the Old Town School of Folk Music.

216
00:26:19.060 --> 00:26:21.699
Thomas Adler: And before I could even drive, I took

217
00:26:21.960 --> 00:26:29.200
Thomas Adler: you know, the Illinois Central commuter train to downtown, and then a bus, and then a transfer to another bus, and…

218
00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:39.800
Thomas Adler: And got myself to the Old Town School and said, well, I want to learn how to play this five-string banjo. And they said, oh, we can teach you that. And I said, I want to play like Earl Scruggs. And they said, oh, no, we don't do that.

219
00:26:39.880 --> 00:26:49.470
Thomas Adler: we can… we play this old-time claw hammer-style banjo, you know, and I said, that's not what I'm after. And they said, well, we can't help. So…

220
00:26:49.850 --> 00:26:53.450
Thomas Adler: They didn't know anything about it at that time, so…

221
00:26:53.620 --> 00:27:06.439
Thomas Adler: So they were no help. You know, eventually I found some people that could show me a little bit, and I started hanging out at an important music store on the south side called The Fret Shop.

222
00:27:06.750 --> 00:27:14.069
Thomas Adler: And… practically one note at a time, people would show me one little thing, you know, and I'd…

223
00:27:14.430 --> 00:27:16.870
Thomas Adler: learned that, and I'd learn another thing.

224
00:27:17.090 --> 00:27:18.080
Thomas Adler: So…

225
00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:29.810
Thomas Adler: at any rate, the bluegrass music came slowly but powerfully into my life. Starting… I guess I… to this day, I date it around the time

226
00:27:30.540 --> 00:27:39.159
Thomas Adler: when I was around 11 years old, so that would have been 1958 or so, when I really got swept up into bluegrass banjo and the sound of

227
00:27:39.490 --> 00:27:43.080
Thomas Adler: Flatten Scruggs, and then Bill Monroe, and other bluegrass

228
00:27:43.400 --> 00:27:47.419
Thomas Adler: artists, you know, and I'm still following it to this day.

229
00:27:47.820 --> 00:27:50.580
Thomas Adler: Still involved with it in many, many ways.

230
00:27:50.970 --> 00:27:57.050
Thomas Adler: So… That's, that's, the early influences.

231
00:27:57.780 --> 00:28:03.680
Thomas Adler: My early education, I think, was your next topic on your list of questions.

232
00:28:03.810 --> 00:28:06.950
Thomas Adler: Well, I… my earliest education was at

233
00:28:07.140 --> 00:28:15.720
Thomas Adler: the elementary school that was literally across the street from our house at 73rd and Jeffrey, Bryn Mawr Public School.

234
00:28:16.210 --> 00:28:28.409
Thomas Adler: Which no longer exists. The building is there, but it, it, I don't know quite when it happened, but it stopped being a public school, and turned into some kind of

235
00:28:28.610 --> 00:28:30.850
Thomas Adler: Private institution.

236
00:28:31.370 --> 00:28:40.319
Thomas Adler: you know, they… I don't know quite what it is, but there is no Bryn Mawr Public School anymore. So,

237
00:28:40.930 --> 00:28:44.290
Thomas Adler: I wish there were such a place.

238
00:28:46.010 --> 00:28:51.480
Thomas Adler: Yeah, once again, I keep, Clicking other things and losing…

239
00:28:52.630 --> 00:28:57.129
Thomas Adler: the screen that I'm trying to see you on. Let me get it back here.

240
00:28:59.380 --> 00:29:06.939
Thomas Adler: the Zoom… oh, there it is, the Zoom screen. Okay, so I went to, Bryn Mawr Public School.

241
00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:12.029
Thomas Adler: through 8th grade, which is as much as we had, I had…

242
00:29:12.590 --> 00:29:24.469
Thomas Adler: a serious medical problem when I was going into 8th grade. I had a problem that turned out to be a herniated disc in my back.

243
00:29:24.610 --> 00:29:25.450
Thomas Adler: which…

244
00:29:25.630 --> 00:29:40.560
Thomas Adler: you know, I was about 12 years old or something like that, and it went undiagnosed for a long time, even though my parents were both physicians, they didn't know quite what was wrong. And I never had pain in my back, just in my knee, that was referred from

245
00:29:41.020 --> 00:29:44.910
Thomas Adler: You know, probably a disc pressing on a nerve in my back.

246
00:29:45.060 --> 00:29:53.779
Thomas Adler: And they took me to various physicians who misdiagnosed it for a few months, and then finally, a neurosurgeon,

247
00:29:54.150 --> 00:29:59.310
Thomas Adler: figured out what was going on, and ultimately, I had some surgery.

248
00:29:59.490 --> 00:30:16.209
Thomas Adler: that took care of it. I was in the hospital a long time, and I still have a big, long scar on my back from the surgery then. Now they can do it with a teeny little incision, but it was… back then, it was a major thing. I was in the hospital for weeks, and

249
00:30:16.290 --> 00:30:19.500
Thomas Adler: But after that was done,

250
00:30:19.890 --> 00:30:34.380
Thomas Adler: then… and I was always a pretty good student, and I was about done with 8th grade, and my parents… my older brother, Peter, had gone on to, the local high school, South Shore High.

251
00:30:34.490 --> 00:30:36.799
Thomas Adler: And I went there, I think, for…

252
00:30:37.140 --> 00:30:41.590
Thomas Adler: one year, or maybe even just half a year, I don't know what it was, but…

253
00:30:41.690 --> 00:30:53.200
Thomas Adler: But my folks thought that I had some potential for more, and they, reached into their wallets and sprung for,

254
00:30:53.490 --> 00:31:01.380
Thomas Adler: for me to go to an expensive alternative, which was the University of Chicago Laboratory High School.

255
00:31:01.690 --> 00:31:09.400
Thomas Adler: Now, lab school, as we called it, actually had a program that ran from kindergarten all the way through high school.

256
00:31:09.600 --> 00:31:14.329
Thomas Adler: and of course, the University of Chicago University,

257
00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:29.280
Thomas Adler: But, you know, I didn't get in there until I was a sophomore, in high school, so I joined… there was a small group, you know, the whole high school was about 125 or 130

258
00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:34.789
Thomas Adler: people, very small. But it was a wonderful school for high school.

259
00:31:34.840 --> 00:31:52.290
Thomas Adler: And I made… I had some good friends there, some of whom I played music with. Again, there were a few folks there that… that were, like me, into folk music and… and at least, marginally into the bluegrass music that I was consumed with by that time.

260
00:31:52.490 --> 00:31:53.490
Thomas Adler: So…

261
00:31:53.850 --> 00:32:03.219
Thomas Adler: the institution then was, was, lab school for me for the rest of high school. And then, beyond that, I,

262
00:32:03.530 --> 00:32:13.040
Thomas Adler: I applied to, well, I forget all the schools I applied to, but I ended up going off for a couple years to Carleton College in Minnesota.

263
00:32:13.380 --> 00:32:21.920
Thomas Adler: I didn't apply myself very well at Carleton College, and so… my father.

264
00:32:21.920 --> 00:32:24.609
Julie Stout: What did you… what did you study at Carleton?

265
00:32:24.610 --> 00:32:37.110
Thomas Adler: Well, the first year, it was, I had vague ideas of being pre-med, so I studied biology and maybe some chemistry, but I, as I say, I didn't really apply myself.

266
00:32:37.210 --> 00:32:42.919
Thomas Adler: And didn't do very well in terms of my grades. I just… I slacked off too much.

267
00:32:43.320 --> 00:32:44.470
Thomas Adler: But,

268
00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:57.300
Thomas Adler: And so, after a couple years there, I transferred. My father was very annoyed at my poor performance, you know, in terms of grades, and the costs were high.

269
00:32:57.430 --> 00:33:05.190
Thomas Adler: And so, he said he's not going to put up with that anymore, and so I ended up transferring then to the University of Illinois in Champaign.

270
00:33:05.680 --> 00:33:24.810
Thomas Adler: Champaign, Illinois. And that's where I finished up. Now, not everything transferred, so even though I had done 2 years at Carleton, it took me 3 more years to graduate from Illinois. However, there was a really bright side, as far as I was concerned.

271
00:33:25.820 --> 00:33:33.930
Thomas Adler: Which was, not only did I… I graduated from Illinois with, let's see, a degree in English,

272
00:33:34.290 --> 00:33:41.920
Thomas Adler: But one of my professors there was a… proved to be a truly important mentor for me.

273
00:33:42.050 --> 00:33:49.549
Thomas Adler: And he was a folklorist and labor, industrial labor scholar named Archie Green.

274
00:33:50.270 --> 00:33:51.700
Thomas Adler: Archie Green.

275
00:33:52.180 --> 00:34:04.240
Thomas Adler: to this day, is well thought of, and he passed away a few years ago, but he was a renowned figure in the world of folklore, and

276
00:34:04.380 --> 00:34:08.820
Thomas Adler: You know, I was… I was involved in all of that. I was…

277
00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:14.489
Thomas Adler: there was a campus folk song club at Illinois, I participated in all that, and…

278
00:34:14.620 --> 00:34:21.299
Thomas Adler: you know, met musicians around there. I became a president of the Campus Folk Song Club, I took…

279
00:34:21.460 --> 00:34:32.580
Thomas Adler: You know, I wrote papers for, both for Archie's classes and… and there were some little publications we had, and he had me writing papers for that.

280
00:34:32.690 --> 00:34:40.969
Thomas Adler: And… And I didn't really realize before I knew Archie that there was an academic field called folklore.

281
00:34:41.310 --> 00:34:48.389
Thomas Adler: And he made me aware of that. And so, by the time I graduated from the University of Illinois.

282
00:34:48.790 --> 00:34:55.769
Thomas Adler: Archie said, you know, you really ought to go on and get a master's in folklore, at the very least, and

283
00:34:55.880 --> 00:35:03.580
Thomas Adler: Archie thought what I should do is go get a master's. There was a master's program in Cooperstown, New York.

284
00:35:04.060 --> 00:35:10.700
Thomas Adler: The Cooperstown Graduate Program. They actually had two different master's programs, one in

285
00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:17.329
Thomas Adler: History museums, you know, for people who wanted to pursue museum studies, and one in folklore.

286
00:35:17.730 --> 00:35:26.749
Thomas Adler: And so, with Archie's strong support, I applied to and got into the folklore program at Cooperstown. It was a one-year program.

287
00:35:27.010 --> 00:35:37.510
Thomas Adler: And Archie thought that after doing that, that I would then go on, perhaps to the PhD program at the University of Pennsylvania.

288
00:35:37.650 --> 00:35:44.209
Thomas Adler: I think I disappointed him, because I did do the master's at Cooperstown, but then I ended up going to

289
00:35:44.320 --> 00:35:47.660
Thomas Adler: Indiana University for the doctorate.

290
00:35:47.850 --> 00:35:50.370
Thomas Adler: And, of course, that's where I met Dawson.

291
00:35:50.590 --> 00:35:57.730
Thomas Adler: And… Dorrison, I think, in his… in fact, in the Folklore Forum issue, where he talks about

292
00:35:57.850 --> 00:36:04.319
Thomas Adler: the Gary gang, he even mentions that I have, you know, came in with an MA from Cooperstown.

293
00:36:04.430 --> 00:36:16.269
Thomas Adler: So, Dawson knew, you know, before I ever met Dawson, he knew that I was an MA folklore student, he knew that I had a strong interest in music.

294
00:36:16.360 --> 00:36:29.250
Thomas Adler: And he knew about the bluegrass music, or southern hillbilly, Appalachian music interests, so all of that was stuff that Dawson knew about me before I ever met him.

295
00:36:29.440 --> 00:36:43.110
Thomas Adler: You know, when I got there. Because, I guess, you know, I don't know what was said in the communications, but the director at Cooperstown, the folklore director, there was a man named,

296
00:36:43.220 --> 00:36:56.340
Thomas Adler: Well, the actual program director was Lewis Jones, but then there was Bruce Buckley, who did the folklore program, and I'm sure they both wrote supportive letters to Dawson that helped me get into Indiana.

297
00:36:56.360 --> 00:37:06.619
Thomas Adler: And so all of this was known to Dawson, and Buckley and Jones were both mentors. I will mention, as well, that

298
00:37:06.740 --> 00:37:13.830
Thomas Adler: while I was at Cooperstown, I met one of the museum students there, a…

299
00:37:13.980 --> 00:37:21.570
Thomas Adler: woman from Milwaukee, or near Milwaukee, Wisconsin, named Elizabeth Mosby, or Betsy Mosby.

300
00:37:21.720 --> 00:37:23.630
Thomas Adler: And the two of us married.

301
00:37:23.830 --> 00:37:29.340
Thomas Adler: In fact, we married at Cooperstown, there's a…

302
00:37:29.790 --> 00:37:39.000
Thomas Adler: place there that was, at least then, called the Farmer's Museum. They had a museum in Cooperstown with an 1840s

303
00:37:39.120 --> 00:37:47.779
Thomas Adler: church as part of the museum, and that's where we married, and so we have a lot of photos there, including photos that our classmates took, and

304
00:37:49.330 --> 00:38:00.910
Thomas Adler: Lou Jones and his wife took photos and sent them all to us. Part of the program there was helping us develop photographic skills, so…

305
00:38:01.100 --> 00:38:08.550
Thomas Adler: you know, so all our classmates took photos and shared them with us, so we had a lot of photos, and all of those are in my iMatch.

306
00:38:08.550 --> 00:38:11.750
Julie Stout: I love that, yeah. What year did you get married?

307
00:38:11.990 --> 00:38:13.370
Thomas Adler: 197.

308
00:38:13.370 --> 00:38:14.230
Julie Stout: Okay.

309
00:38:14.230 --> 00:38:17.050
Thomas Adler: And so, I think that's…

310
00:38:18.340 --> 00:38:20.440
Thomas Adler: That's the biggest part of the biographic.

311
00:38:20.440 --> 00:38:21.180
Julie Stout: Yeah!

312
00:38:21.180 --> 00:38:23.760
Thomas Adler: You know, that I can tell you about.

313
00:38:23.760 --> 00:38:26.990
Julie Stout: I had, a follow-up question, if that's okay for you.

